<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ920214-0104</DOCNO><DOCID>920214-0104.</DOCID><HL>   New York City Panel   Accuses Delta Air   Of Discrimination</HL><DATE>02/14/92</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C19</SO><CO>   DAL LABOR</CO><MS>CONSUMER CYCLICAL (CYC)</MS><IN>AIRLINES (AIR)</IN><NS>LABOR, UNIONS, STRIKES, WAGES, RECRUITMENT (LAB)</NS><RE>GEORGIA (GA)NORTH AMERICA (NME)NEW YORK (NY)UNITED STATES (US)</RE><LP>   NEW YORK -- The New York City Commission on Human Rightssaid it filed 50 complaints against Delta Air Lines foralleged discriminatory practices against former Pan AmericanWorld Airways employees.   The employees in mid-December had complained that Deltahad asked discriminatory and improper questions when it wasinterviewing former Pan Am employees after purchasing some ofthe airline's operations.</LP><TEXT>   A Delta spokesman denied that the company took anydiscriminatory actions against the Pan Am job applicants.&quot;That's simply not the case, and we think the commission willagree with us.&quot; He said the company is responding toindividual complaints as the commission sends them to Delta.   A commission spokesman said the employees, most of themNew York residents, alleged that some women were asked ifthey took birth control pills and if they had had abortions.Others were asked whether their parents were divorced, andsingle women were asked about plans for marriage and abouttheir relationships with their boyfriends.   A city ordinance prohibits bias on the basis of age,disability, marital status and other categories. Thecommission said Delta could be liable for civil penalties ofup to $250,000 for each illegal act, as well as compensatorydamages. And a city judge could order reinstatement ofemployees.   The commission said it expects to file 25 additionalcomplaints soon. The employees were in jobs ranging fromflight attendant and reservation agent to pilot, flightengineer and dispatcher.</TEXT></DOC>